word_summaries_chapter_100:
  100:1:1:"The first word of verse (100:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and active participle. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"by\" and is used to form an oath. The active participle is feminine plural and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn dāl wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع د و</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  100:1:2:"The second word of verse (100:1) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḍād bā ḥā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ض ب ح</span>)."
  100:2:1:"The first word of verse (100:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and active participle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The form IV active participle is feminine plural and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw rā yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ر ي</span>)."
  100:2:2:"The second word of verse (100:2) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf dāl ḥā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق د ح</span>)."
  100:3:1:"The first word of verse (100:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and active participle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The form IV active participle is feminine plural and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ghayn yā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">غ ي ر</span>)."
  100:3:2:"The second word of verse (100:3) is an indefinite masculine time adverb and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The time adverb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād bā ḥā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص ب ح</span>)."
  100:4:1:"The first word of verse (100:4) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person feminine plural. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">thā wāw rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ث و ر</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">النون</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  100:4:2:"The second word of verse (100:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and personal pronoun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">bi</i> is usually translated as \"with\" or \"by\". The personal pronoun is third person masculine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  100:4:3:"The third word of verse (100:4) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn qāf ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ق ع</span>)."
  100:5:1:"The first word of verse (100:5) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person feminine plural. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw sīn ṭā</i> (<span class=\"at\">و س ط</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">النون</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
